We’re going to create a TLS certificate for a Kubernetes user, get it signed, and make it usable.

Step 0 — Overview (Why we do this)

Think of Kubernetes like a club with a locked door:

You can only get in if you have a key (TLS certificate)
Kubernetes uses certificates to check who you are and what you can do

So what we’re doing:

Make a private key = your personal key
Make a CSR (certificate request) = a formal request to join the club
Submit it to Kubernetes
Approve it
Get a signed certificate
Use it to log in
Step 1 — Generate a private key
openssl genrsa -out user.key 2048

Explanation:

openssl genrsa → Generate RSA private key
-out user.key → Save it to a file called user.key
2048 → Key size (big enough for security)

This is your secret key, don’t share it with anyone.

Step 2 — Create a CSR (Certificate Signing Request)
openssl req -new -key user.key -out user.csr -subj "/CN=dahir/O=dev-group"

Explanation:

openssl req -new → Make a new certificate request
-key user.key → Use the private key we just made
-out user.csr → Save the CSR to user.csr
-subj "/CN=dahir/O=dev-group" → Fill the info:
CN=dahir → Your username in Kubernetes
O=dev-group → The group you belong to (used for permissions)

Think of this as filling out a form to request a club membership.

Step 3 — Encode the CSR for Kubernetes
cat user.csr | base64 | tr -d '\n'

Explanation:

cat user.csr → Read the CSR file
base64 → Turn it into a string of letters and numbers (Kubernetes likes this)
tr -d '\n' → Remove line breaks (Kubernetes wants it all on one line)

This produces a long string you can paste into a YAML file.

Step 4 — Create Kubernetes CSR YAML
apiVersion: certificates.k8s.io/v1
kind: CertificateSigningRequest
metadata:
  name: dahir-csr
spec:
  request: <PASTE_BASE64_CSR_HERE>
  signerName: kubernetes.io/kube-apiserver-client
  expirationSeconds: 86400
  usages:
    - client auth

Explanation line by line:

apiVersion: certificates.k8s.io/v1 → Kubernetes API that handles certificate requests
kind: CertificateSigningRequest → This is a CSR object
metadata.name: dahir-csr → Name for the request (must be unique)
spec.request → Paste the base64-encoded CSR here
signerName: kubernetes.io/kube-apiserver-client → Tells Kubernetes: “This cert will be used to talk to the API server”
expirationSeconds: 86400 → Certificate valid for 24 hours (86400 seconds)
usages: client auth → This certificate will be used to authenticate a client

Think of this YAML as the official request form for Kubernetes.

Step 5 — Apply the CSR to Kubernetes
kubectl apply -f csr.yaml

Explanation:

Sends the CSR YAML to Kubernetes
Kubernetes now knows you want a certificate
Step 6 — Approve the CSR
kubectl certificate approve dahir-csr

Explanation:

Tells Kubernetes: “Yes, approve this certificate request”
Kubernetes signs your CSR and generates a certificate

Without approval, Kubernetes ignores your request — like the club manager hasn’t signed your form yet.

Step 7 — Retrieve the signed certificate
kubectl get csr dahir-csr -o jsonpath='{.status.certificate}' | base64 -d > user.crt

Explanation:

kubectl get csr dahir-csr → Get the CSR object
-o jsonpath='{.status.certificate}' → Extract the signed certificate from the status
base64 -d > user.crt → Decode it and save it as user.crt

Now user.crt + user.key = your login credentials.

Step 8 — Verify your certificate
openssl x509 -in user.crt -text -noout

Explanation:

Shows the certificate info
You can check CN, expiration, and usages

Make sure CN=dahir and usage includes Client Authentication.

Step 9 — Use the certificate in kubeconfig
kubectl config set-credentials dahir \
  --client-certificate=user.crt \
  --client-key=user.key

Explanation:

Registers your certificate + key in kubeconfig
Now you can use kubectl as user dahir
Step 10 — Bind permissions (RBAC)
apiVersion: rbac.authorization.k8s.io/v1
kind: RoleBinding
metadata:
  name: dahir-binding
  namespace: default
subjects:
- kind: User
  name: dahir
  apiGroup: rbac.authorization.k8s.io
roleRef:
  kind: Role
  name: view
  apiGroup: rbac.authorization.k8s.io

Explanation:

Tells Kubernetes what the user can do
RoleBinding attaches user dahir → role view
Without this, your certificate is valid but you can’t do anything
✅ Key Takeaways for Beginners
Private key = your secret key
CSR = the form you submit
YAML = the official request
Approve → get certificate
RBAC → gives permissions

Now you have a real Kubernetes TLS certificate setup, explained like a beginner could follow.
